== Verb ==
'''spur''', '''spurred'''

1. To [[prod]] (''esp.'' a [[horse]]) in the side or flank, with the intent to urge motion or haste, to [[gig]].
     ''Her horse hesitated at the stream, so she spurred it across.''

2. To urge or encourage, as if of a [[horse]]
     ''His fiery speech spurred the team to play an inspired second half.''

== Noun ==
'''spur'''

1. A rigid implement, often roughly y-shaped, that is fixed to one's heel for purposes of prodding a horse.  Often worn by, and emblematic of, the [[cowboy]].
     ''He told everyone at the dance that he had earned his spurs, and he wouldn't take them off just because they asked.''

2. An appendage or spike pointing rearward, near the foot, for instance that of a [[rooster]].

3. Any protruding part connected at one end, for instance a highway that extends from another highway into a city